	 Hematology diseases do&nbsp;not have any unique symptoms, that is&nbsp;why they are quite difficult to&nbsp;diagnose. Only a&nbsp;doctor specialized in&nbsp;this medical area can reveal the changes in&nbsp;your body caused be&nbsp;hematologic disorders and start appropriate treatment on&nbsp;time.
</p>
<p>
	 Hematology consultation is&nbsp;necessary for every woman not only during her pregnancy but also at&nbsp;the stage of&nbsp;family planning if&nbsp;you want to&nbsp;prepare properly. During the period, there are many changes in&nbsp;the blood count and coagulation test. Therefore, it&nbsp;is&nbsp;important to&nbsp;differentiate normal physiological changes from developing pathology on&nbsp;time.
</p>
<p>
	 It&nbsp;is&nbsp;necessary to&nbsp;make an&nbsp;appointment with a&nbsp;hematologist if&nbsp;you plan a&nbsp;family and have had one or&nbsp;more of&nbsp;the following conditions in&nbsp;your medical history:
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Several miscarriages.</li>
	<li>IVF failures.</li>
	<li>Thrombophlebites during your previous pregnancies.</li>
</ul>
<p>
	 It&nbsp;is&nbsp;also necessary to&nbsp;get a&nbsp;Hematology Consultation if&nbsp;you have one or&nbsp;more of&nbsp;the following symptoms:
</p>
<ul>
	<li>Sudden weakness, easy tiredness, chronic fatigue.</li>
	<li>Weight and/or appetite loss.</li>
	<li>Skin pallor.</li>
	<li>Excessive sweating.</li>
	<li>Fingertip numbness and/or tingling.</li>
	<li>Bruises for no&nbsp;reason.</li>
	<li>Regular nose bleedings.</li>
	<li>In&nbsp;girls and women&nbsp;— regular menstrual cycle disorders.</li>
	<li>Slow healing, excessive and/or difficult to&nbsp;stop bleedings in&nbsp;case of&nbsp;cuts and wounds.</li>
	<li>Intensive face redness, cyanosis (bluish or&nbsp;purplish discolouration of&nbsp;the skin) unrelated to&nbsp;internal diseases.</li>
	<li>Frequent headaches of&nbsp;unknown origin.</li>
	<li>Long period of&nbsp;fever for no&nbsp;reason.</li>
	<li>Frequent colds and long «banal infections».</li>
	<li>Swollen lymph nodes in&nbsp;neck, groin or&nbsp;armpit areas.</li>
</ul>
<p>
	 At&nbsp;the initial consultation, our doctor will listen to&nbsp;your complaints and ask questions about your health. Please bring any recent blood tests you might have (preferably made no&nbsp;earlier than 14&nbsp;days ago). If&nbsp;necessary, you will be&nbsp;referred for additional tests, after which our hematologist will determine a&nbsp;treatment strategy for you.
</p>
<p>
	 If&nbsp;you are pregnant, our hematologist will check for rhesus and ABO incompatibility between the mother and the fetus, give recommendations on&nbsp;how to&nbsp;support you and your future baby if&nbsp;hematology problems already exist or&nbsp;prescribe sparing treatment.
</p>
<p>
	 Please, use our <a href="#contactus" data-modal-open="">contact form</a> to&nbsp;make an&nbsp;appointment. Our International Manager will contact you to&nbsp;offer convenient date and time.
</p>
<p>
	 You can also make an&nbsp;appointment for the online consultation. However, please, remember that an&nbsp;online consultation cannot be&nbsp;equal to&nbsp;actually seeing a&nbsp;doctor.
